ory. For some widows, government compensation in the form of military-style awards sufficed. For others, their own deprivations, combined with those suffered by widows living in other nations, became the touchstone of a transnational awareness of the absurdity of war and the need to prevent it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aNationalismxHistoryy20th century. 0aTransnationalismxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar widowsxGovernment policyzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar widowsxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar widowsxGovernment policyzWestern countriesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspectszGermany. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xWomen. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814749050423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814749050.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK